In [ ]:
def visualize_input(i, y):
    img = X_train[i].reshape(28,28)
    plt.imshow(img, cmap='gray')
    plt.title(f"Label : {y[i]}")
    width, height = img.shape
    thresh = img.max()/2.5
    for x in range(width):
        for y in range(height):
            plt.annotate(str(img[x][y]), xy=(y,x),
                        horizontalalignment='center',
                        verticalalignment='center',
                        color='white' if img[x][y]<thresh else 'black')
    plt.xticks([])
    plt.yticks([])
In [ ]:
fig = plt.figure(figsize = (15,11)) 
visualize_input(1, y_train)

The plot given above shows pixel values with colors. With these pixel values, we can see the shades in the image. Here 255 shows pure white color whereas less than 255 shows different shades of grey. 0 pixel value means pure black color whith is the background color in this case.

Initial Model Definition:¶

In [ ]:
tf.random.set_seed(72)

model = keras.Sequential([
    layers.Dense(512, activation="relu"),
    layers.Dense(10, activation="softmax")
])

Sequential: Defines a sequence of layers in the neural network.
Dense: Adds a layer of neurons
Each layer of neurons need an activation function to tell them what to do. There are a lot of options, but just use these for now:

ReLU means:
if x > 0:
return x

else:
return 0

Compile model:

In [ ]:
model.compile(optimizer="rmsprop",  
              loss="sparse_categorical_crossentropy",
              metrics=["accuracy"])

Optimizer - This is how the model is updated based on the data it sees and its loss function.
Loss function - This calculates how accurate the model is during training.
Metrics - Used to monitor the training and testing steps.

This plot shows the loss and accuracy fluctuations for each epoch for both training and validation data.
For loss graph, we can see that initially the loss was high (almost 0.6) for the 1st epoch, however it gradually decreased after each epoch run to less than 0.3.

In the accuracy graph, we can also see a gradual increase in both the training and validation data accuracy which is more than 0.88 i.e it is more than 88% accurate.

For the model that we defined earlier, we can see that the least loss value is at epoch 4. However, we are not sure if after epoch 4 we will reach an optimal solution or can we have an epoch value which further decrease in loss.

Here we can see overfitting, where after some number of epochs, the loss on training dataset decreased, however, the loss on validation dataset started to increase. This means that our model will perform very well on the training data however, it will not do well on validation data due to over-fitting.
Our 1st best model therefore, is saved in 'best_model1.hdf5' file which saves model based on the minimum value of validation loss.

In [ ]:
val_loss = history1.history['val_loss']

min_loss1_epoch = val_loss.index(min_loss1) + 1  

print(f"Minimum validation loss: {min_loss1} at epoch: {min_loss1_epoch}")

Define and fit Model 3:¶

In [ ]:
checkpoint_filepath = 'best_model3.hdf5'  

model_checkpoint_callback = ModelCheckpoint(
    filepath=checkpoint_filepath,
    save_weights_only=False,  
    monitor='val_loss',
    mode='min', 
    save_best_only=True)
In [ ]:
image_rows = 28
image_cols = 28
image_shape = (image_rows,image_cols,1) 

X_train_new = X_train.reshape(X_train.shape[0],*image_shape)
X_test_new = X_test.reshape(X_test.shape[0],*image_shape)
X_validate_new = X_validate.reshape(X_validate.shape[0],*image_shape)

This is done inorder to fit the model's expected input which in form -> (batch, height, width, channels)
Reshape is used to change the data in flatten form into a structured form.

In [ ]:
model3 = Sequential([
    Conv2D(filters=32,kernel_size=3,activation='relu',input_shape = image_shape),
    MaxPooling2D(pool_size=2) ,
    Dropout(0.2),
    Flatten(), 
    Dense(32,activation='relu'),
    Dense(10,activation = 'softmax')
    
])

The first layer Conv2D is for convolutional layer with 32 filters, kernel size is 3x3 and activation function used is ReLU. This layer is used to extract the features from images.
MaxPooling2D is the pooling layer of size 2x2.
Dropout is the regulation layer which helps prevent overfitting
Flatten is used to flatten the matrix into a vector before being fed into the dense layer.
Dense is the fully-connected layer which uses ReLU activation function

In [ ]:
model3.compile(loss ='sparse_categorical_crossentropy', optimizer="adam", metrics =['accuracy'])
In [ ]:
history3 = model3.fit(
    X_train_new,
    y_train,
    batch_size=128,
    epochs=40,
    verbose=1,
    validation_data=(X_validate_new,y_validate),
    callbacks=[model_checkpoint_callback]
)

For the other classes the prediction is pretty good.

6. High Precision for class 5:¶

We saw earlier that for test data:
Precision: 0.98
Recall: 0.92

To increase the precision without changing or retraining model, we studied that we need to increase threshold.

In [ ]:
y_scores = y_test_pred[:, 5]
y5 = (y_test == 5)

threshold = 0.6 
y_pred_high_precision = (y_scores > threshold)

precision = precision_score(y5, y_pred_high_precision)
recall = recall_score(y5, y_pred_high_precision)

print(f"When threshold increased to: {threshold}\nPrecision: {precision:.4f}\nRecall: {recall:.4f}")

When threshold increased to: 0.6
Precision: 0.9911
Recall: 0.8940

By doing this the precision value increased from 0.98 to 0.99.
Precision increases because the values with high confidence of being positive will be classified and recall i.e the ratio (tp/tp+np) decreases.

7. High Recall for Class 5:¶

To increase the recall value, decrease threshold

In [ ]:
y_scores = y_test_pred[:, 5]
y5 = (y_test == 5)

threshold = 0.3
y_pred_high_recall = (y_scores > threshold)

precision = precision_score(y5, y_pred_high_recall)
recall = recall_score(y5, y_pred_high_recall)

print(f"When threshold decreased to: {threshold}\nPrecision: {precision:.4f}\nRecall: {recall:.4f}")

When threshold decreased to: 0.3
Precision: 0.9778
Recall: 0.9250

Recall increased from 0.92 to 0.93
When the threshold value is decreased, recall increases whereas precision decreases.
It is because all those which had low predicted probability of will also be classified as positive.
